13 (3) An assessment of the minor's intelligence and maturity level, when relevant;
14 (4) The minor's age, developmental state, and decisionmaking abilities; and
15 (5) Whether the minor has any other factor that affects fitness to proceed.
16 c. A description of abilities and deficits in the following mental competency functions
17 related to the minor's fitness to proceed:
18 (1) The ability to factually and rationally understand and appreciate the nature
19 and object of the proceedings, including the ability to:
20 (a) Understand the role of the participants in the court process, including
21 the roles of the judge, the minor's attorney, the prosecuting attorney,
22 the probation officer, witnesses, and the jury, and to understand the
23 adversarial nature of the process;
24 (b) Appreciate the offense and understand the seriousness of the offense;
25 (c) Understand and realistically appraise the likely outcomes; and
26 (d) Extend thinking into the future.
27 (2) The ability to render meaningful assistance to the minor's attorney in the
28 preparation of the case, including:
29 (a) The ability to disclose to an attorney a reasonably coherent
30 description of facts and events pertaining to the charge, as perceived
31 by the minor;
